TI  - Study on the Pricing Strategy for Closed-loop Supply Chain of Power Batteries Based on the 'Tri-Credit' Policy
AU  - Fan, Jiajing
AU  - Yan, Ziwei
AU  - Wang, Youyan
T2  - INTERNATIONAL JOURNAL OF SYSTEMS SCIENCE-OPERATIONS & LOGISTICS
AB  - While production and sales are booming of NEVs, the issue of recycling retired power batteries from NEVs has also emerged. A 'Recycling credit' has been introduced on the basis of the 'Dual Credit' policy, forming a 'Tri-Credit' policy. Targeting the secondary closed-loop supply chain of power batteries composed of manufacturers and retailers, Stackelberg game theory models were constructed for two recycling modes. The results show that: (1) Both NEV credits and CAFC credits can enhance the attractiveness of NEVs to consumers, but they do not promote the recycling of power batteries; (2) Recycling credits and recycling ratio requirement both contribute to the attractiveness of NEVs and the recycling of power batteries. However, the retailer recycling mode is more conducive to boosting NEV sales, the manufacturer recycling mode is more effective in promoting power battery recycling. Under the retailer recycling mode, the pricing of NEVs and power battery recycling is more sensitive to changes in recycling credits and recycling ratio requirement; (3) In both recycling modes, the prices of NEVs are more sensitive to changes in recycling ratio requirement than to recycling credit. At last, based on the results, specific strategies are proposed at the government and NEV manufacturer levels, respectively.
