TI  - Strategic battery procurement and recycling for a new entrant considering incumbent competition with limited capacity
AU  - Xing, Peng
AU  - Wang, Mingxing
T2  - COMPUTERS & INDUSTRIAL ENGINEERING
AB  - The rapid growth of the new energy vehicle industry highlights the critical challenges of securing battery supply and managing recycling. While extant literature often examines these issues in isolation, a critical gap exists in understanding how a new entrant can strategically integrate these decisions under competitive pressure. This study employs a game-theoretic model to examine how a new entrant's battery procurement strategy (sourcing from an external supplier or an incumbent with limited capacity) interacts with the choice of reverse channel recycling modes (third-party or joint venture). Equilibrium decisions and profits are derived under different battery capacity zones. The findings indicate that the new entrant's optimal mode selection is influenced by the competition degree with the incumbent and the prevailing battery capacity of the incumbent. Contrary to intuition, we find that a joint venture recycling mode often yields superior profitability for the new entrant by improving its bargaining position and operational synergy. Furthermore, we demonstrate that excessively stringent government recycling rate targets or reward-penalty intensities can be counterproductive, inadvertently dampening profitability across the supply chain. This research contributes to the literature by offering a unified strategic framework for the new entrant, highlighting how integrated procurement and recycling decisions can serve as a competitive lever in the face of supply constraints and market competition.
