TI  - Reverse channel choice for retired electric vehicle batteries under a deposit refund system
AU  - Li, Xin
AU  - Du, Jianbang
AU  - Liu, Pei
AU  - Yue, Xiongping
AU  - Ji, Xue
AU  - Song, Chao
AU  - Ma, Chuang
T2  - COMPUTERS & INDUSTRIAL ENGINEERING
AB  - As the electric vehicle industry has expanded rapidly, managing large-scale retired power battery collection has emerged as a critical challenge. Six collection models incorporating a deposit refund system were examined in this study: manufacturer collection (Model M), retailer collection (Model R), third-party collection (Model T), manufacturer and retailer cocollection (Model MR), manufacturer and third-party cocollection (Model MT), and retailer and third-party cocollection (Model RT). Through a Stackelberg game analysis, we revealed three key findings: (1) Deposit increases negatively impact the collection rate and total social welfare, whereas collection subsidies exhibit dual effects, increasing the collection rate but creating an inverted U-shaped relationship with social welfare. Notably, the MR model has the lowest optimal subsidy. (2) Collection model selection depends on objectives. From the perspective of the collection rate, Model MR is the optimal choice. From the perspective of total social welfare, the best collection model depends on subsidy level: Model MR outperforms the others under low subsidy conditions, while Model RT becomes preferable when subsidies are relatively high, and Model MT performs best at intermediate subsidy levels. (3) Higher consumer environmental awareness consistently increases the collection rate and improves total social welfare across all models. Specifically, Model RT exhibits the fastest total social welfare growth rate. When the free return quantity reaches a certain threshold, Model RT's total social welfare surpasses that of Model M.
